  "text": "The serialization boundary between Kafka and Flink is defined by these key interfaces and classes:\n\n**Kafka Interfaces (org.apache.kafka.common.serialization):**\n1. `Serializer<T>` (github.com/sg-evals/kafka--0753c489/clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/serialization/Serializer.java) - Interface defining how objects are converted to bytes for Kafka. Core method: `byte[] serialize(String topic, T data)`.\n\n2. `Deserializer<T>` (github.com/sg-evals/kafka--0753c489/clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/common/serialization/Deserializer.java) - Interface defining how bytes are converted back to objects. Core method: `T deserialize(String topic, byte[] data)`.\n\n**Flink Abstraction (org.apache.flink.api.common.serialization):**\n3. `DeserializationSchema<T>` (github.com/sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc/flink-core/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/api/common/serialization/DeserializationSchema.java) - Flink's source-agnostic abstraction for deserialization. Core method: `T deserialize(byte[] message)`. This interface is designed to work with any data source (Kafka, files, sockets, etc.) and provides type information through ResultTypeQueryable.\n\n**Bridge/Wrapper Implementation:**\n4. `EventDeSerializationSchema` (github.com/sg-evals/flink--0cc95fcc/flink-examples/flink-examples-streaming/src/main/java/org/apache/flink/streaming/examples/statemachine/kafka/EventDeSerializationSchema.java) - A concrete implementation that shows how to wrap Kafka deserialization logic. It implements both DeserializationSchema<Event> and SerializationSchema<Event>.\n\n**Key Difference at the Boundary:**\nKafka's Deserializer is topic-aware (requires topic name as a parameter), while Flink's DeserializationSchema is topic-agnostic and designed to work with multiple data sources. Flink's KafkaSource connector bridges this gap using `KafkaRecordDeserializationSchema.valueOnly()`, which adapts Kafka-specific deserialization to Flink's DeserializationSchema interface. This allows